[2] North Carolina (Orange County)
Date: Mon 19 Mar 2012
Source: Chapelboro [edited]
http://www.chapelboro.com/Whooping-Cough-Confirmed-at-Carrboro-Elementary/12586474


"We have had 2 cases in the same grade level that have been confirmed," says Community Health Services Supervisor Judy Butler.

Last November 2011, WCHL reported that a kindergartner in the Chapel Hill-Carrboro school system had developed the disease. That student was also at Carrboro elementary.

Butler says school system parents should take a few basic precautions. "Have your child fully vaccinated and to be alert for symptoms in your child and if they do have symptoms, consult your physician." says Butler. "Keep the child away from infants, pregnant women, and people are immunocompromised in particular. If whooping cough is strongly suspected, they need to stay away from everyone."

On average, Orange County sees about 3 cases of whooping cough per year. But Butler says those numbers have been going up in recent years.

"2008-2009 was a big year; there were 29 cases. Then in 2010, 2; 2011 we had 3 and we've had more in 2012," says Butler. "Alamance [County] is also having a significant outbreak."

Although the pertussis vaccine isn't 100 percent effective, Butler says those who have been immunized tend to have milder cases if they do develop the disease. All North Carolina children are required by law to receive a vaccination.

[Byline: Anne Brenner]

